  6:08 AM
The problem with removing outliers, is that to determine which points are outliers, you need to have a good model of what is or is not "good data". If you are unsure about the model (which factors should be included, what structure does the model have, what are the assumptions of the noise, ...), then you cannot be sure about your outliers. Those outliers might just be samples that are trying to tell you that your model is wrong. In other words: removing outliers will reinforce your (incorrect!) model, instead of allowing you to obtain new insights!
6:09
Another option, is to use robust statistics. E.g. the mean and standard deviation are sensitive to outliers, other metrics of "location" and "spread" are more robust. E.g. instead of the mean, use the median. Instead of standard deviation, use inter-quartile range. Instead of standard least-squares regression, you could use robust regression. All those robust methods de-emphasize the outliers in one way or another, but they typically do not remove the outlier data completely (i.e. a good thing).
6:09
I agree with @pbobba
6:10
You can do it in a sensitivity analysis and compare the results of the two analyses.

REMINDER: Talk by Prof Marco Canini tomorrow (Friday).You are cordially invited to the following talk by Prof Marco Canini, hosted by VMware Research GroupTitle: Scaling Distributed Machine Learning with In-Network Aggregation
Date: Fri, March 29
Time: 10:30am-11:30am (Pacific time)
Location: Palo Alto, Creekside F - Pearl (CSF1159)
Zoom: https://VMware.zoom.us/j/428712839Abstract:Training complex machine learning models in parallel is an increasingly important workload. We accelerate distributed parallel training by designing a communication primitive that uses a programmable switch dataplane to execute a key step of the training process. Our approach reduces the volume of exchanged data by aggregating the model updates from multiple workers in the network. We co-design the switch processing with the end-host protocols and ML frameworks to provide a robust, efficient solution that speeds up training by up to 300%, and at least by 20% for a number of real-world benchmark models.Bio:Marco does not know what the next big thing will be. But he's sure that our next-gen computing and networking infrastructure must be a viable platform for it and avoid stifling innovation. Marco's research area is cloud computing, distributed systems and networking. His current interest is in designing better systems support for AI/ML and provide practical implementations deployable in the real-world.Marco is an assistant professor in Computer Science at KAUST. Marco obtained his Ph.D. in computer science and engineering from the University of Genoa in 2009 after spending the last year as a visiting student at the University of Cambridge, Computer Laboratory. He was a postdoctoral researcher at EPFL from 2009 to 2012 and after that a senior research scientist for one year at Deutsche Telekom Innovation Labs & TU Berlin. Before joining KAUST, he was an assistant professor at the UCLouvain. He also held positions at Intel, Microsoft and Google. (edited)

Dear colleagues, you are invited to attend the following talk hosted by VMware Research:Title: Relational Artificial IntelligenceDate: Tuesday, October 15,
Time: 11:00 AM-12:00 PM Pacific
Location: Creekside F, Pearl (CSF1159)
Zoom: https://VMware.zoom.us/j/836852615ABSTRACT:In this talk, Molham Aref will make the case for a first-principles approach to machine learning over relational databases that exploits recent development in database systems and theory. The input to learning classification and regression models is defined by feature extraction queries over relational databases. He casts the machine learning problem as a database problem by decomposing the learning task into a batch of aggregates over the feature extraction query and by computing this batch over the input database. The performance of this approach benefits tremendously from structural properties of the relational data and of the feature extraction query; such properties may be algebraic (semi-ring), combinatorial (hypertree width), or statistical (sampling). This translates to several orders-of-magnitude speed-up over state-of-the-art systems.Speaker Bio:Molham Aref is the Chief Executive Officer of RelationalAI. He has more than 28 years of experience in leading organisations that develop and implement high value machine learning and artificial intelligence solutions across various industries. Prior to RelationalAI he was CEO of LogicBlox and Predictix (now Infor), Optimi (now Ericsson), and co-founder of Brickstream (now FLIR). Molham held senior leadership positions at HNC Software (now FICO) and Retek (now Oracle).

When your data doesn’t fit in memory: the basic techniques
You’re writing software that processes data, and it works fine when you test it on a small sample file. But when you load the real data, your program crashes. The problem is that you don’t have enough memory—if you have 16GB of RAM, you can’t load a 100GB file. At some point the operating system will run out of memory, fail to allocate, and there goes your program. So what can you do? You could spin up a Big Data cluster—all you’ll need to do is: Get a cluster of computers. Spend a week on setup. In many cases, learn a completely new API and rewrite all your code. This can be expensive and frustrating; luckily, in many cases it’s also unnecessary. You need a solution that’s simple and easy:…

We are coming up on the 10AM - 11 AM PDT session for VML by the prominent Dr.Anima Anandkumar (Bren Professor at Caltech and Director, AI research at Nvidia).Next-generation frameworks for Generalizable AIAbstract: The deep-learning revolution has achieved impressive progress through the convergence of data, algorithms, and computing infrastructure. The availability of web-scale labeled data and parallelism of GPUs enabled us to harness the power of neural networks. However, for further progress, we cannot solely rely on bigger models. We need to reduce our dependence on labeled data, and design algorithms that can incorporate more structure and domain knowledge. Examples include tensors, graphs, physical laws, and simulations. I will describe efficient frameworks that enable developers to easily prototype such models, e.g. Tensorly to incorporate tensorized architectures, NVIDIA Isaac to incorporate physically valid simulations and NVIDIA RAPIDS for end-to-end data analytics. What is LeanML?
Lean Machine Learning (LeanML) is an organisational framework that allows Data Science teams to build business-oriented data products through a highly structured process. LeanML is aware of the difficulties of dealing with data-centric workflows and outcomes. It is inspired by techniques and knowhow from multiple disciplines such as quant trading in finance, business intelligence, agile software engineering and strategic consulting.

Hi VMware data and ML community, Today we’re excited to share that Loop, our internal data annotation platform is now open source on Github. High quality annotations are key to the success of today’s supervised ML techniques and Loop makes it easy for you to create and manage annotations for common data types including text, image, tabular, and logs. Getting started takes only a few minutes and anyone within VMware can become an annotator just by logging in. As Loop continues to enable more ML teams within VMware, we want to bring the same benefit to the open source community. To be clear about our project goals and the users we serve, we chose the external project name: Data Annotator for Machine Learning (DAML) and wrote a medium article to introduce the high-level functionality. If you have industry peers who are looking for a data annotation solution, please feel free to share the medium article. We’re looking for your feedback and contributions directly on Github. If you’re working on a machine learning project, consider using Loop today. For any questions or if you want to get involved in the project, please reach out to the lead developer, Julia Li. Regards, 
InstaML Team

Hi all, Vyas Sekar will be giving a talk on Monday Aug 8th 11AM on a topic that might be of interest to this channel:
7:23
Title: Enabling Data-driven Innovation in Product Lifecycles with Synthetic Data
Short blurb: Our conversations with leading enterprise AI vendors across market verticals (e.g., security, telemetry, finance) tell us that at every step along the way, lack of access to realistic and diverse data from multiple deployments hampers innovation; e.g., products trained on data not representative of customer environment, there is no way to quantitatively assess products; machine learning workflows experiences data drift, and product audit/feedback is not quantitative. The result today is poor products, lack of transparency, lots of effort in debugging/reproduction/resolution, and impossibility to share insights across customers. At CMU, we have been leading research on demonstrating the feasibility of using synthetic data using Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) to address these pain points for various tasks (e.g., telemetry, anomaly detection, model training). We have identified and addressed key fidelity, scalability, and privacy challenges and tradeoffs in existing GAN-based approaches. By synthesizing domain-specific insights with recent advances in machine learning and privacy, we identify design choices to tackle these challenges. In this talk, we will present some of the key results from our work in applying these techniques to timeseries datasets and network logs.
 Bio: Vyas Sekar is the Tan Family Professor of Electrical and Computer Engineering in the ECE Department at CMU. His work is broadly at the intersection of networks, systems, and security. His work has been recognized with numerous awards including the SIGCOMM Rising Star Award, NSA Science of Security prize, and the Intel Outstanding Researcher Award. He was most recently the founding co-director of the IoT@Cylab initiative and is a founding co-director of the Future of Enterprise Security Initiative at Cylab.

A problem: nearly all Internet traffic is now TLS-encrypted, and that includes malware C2. Break-and-inspect Intrusion Detection requires complicated client and network configuration, introduces an additional point of failure, creates legal liability, and with the increasing amount of TLS 1.3 traffic is increasingly unreliable.
1 reply
  6 months ago
Nearly every approach to this problem uses machine learning: from ACM, to SANS, to Cisco's Umbrella, to our own Lastline.The ROC curve on the existing approaches isn't great, especially given the additional time it takes a SOC analyst to determine whether a given connection was benign, given only the flow metadata. Deep Learning seems like a good idea, but the limiting factor on that is availability of data.Programming LM's can deal with the data problem by generating puzzles. MuZero did it via self play. GPT-3 brute-forced it by downloading the entire Internet.There's no open sufficiently large dataset for benign TLS connections, AFAIK; especially a dataset representative of modern traffic (which has gone from 50% to 95% in a decade).With the new Carbon Black Cloud XDR sensor shipping, we could start getting a lot of TLS flow metadata. Some basic assumptions, like "flows are benign if there was no alert on the endpoint for +- 1hr" might get us  enough data to train a large model. Alternatively, is there a way to synthesize the data that I haven't thought of?

Papers with Code - MuZero Explained
MuZero is a model-based reinforcement learning algorithm. It builds upon AlphaZero's search and search-based policy iteration algorithms, but incorporates a learned model into the training procedure. The main idea of the algorithm is to predict those aspects of the future that are directly relevant for planning. The model receives the observation (e.g. an image of the Go board or the Atari screen) as an
input and transforms it into a hidden state. The hidden state is then updated iteratively by a recurrent process that receives the previous hidden state and a hypothetical next action. At every one of these steps the model predicts the policy (e.g. the move to play), value function (e.g. the p…

A High-Performance Computing Application in Finance with Virtual GPUs on VMware vSphere | VMware
This article gives the background on technical testing done on a Monte Carlo application in High Performance Computing on VMware vSphere using virtualized GPUs to accelerate its overall performance. We describe an improvement in the application's performance over a bare metal original deployment. The article shows the power of virtualization to scale out parts of applications like this one that are highly parallel in their processing. The two principal types of High Performance Computing application are described also. (63 kB)

Hi folks, our group #bf_radium is hoping to engage with others in VMware to try out what we're building, and see how well it does or doesn't fit your use-case before we start sharing with customers later this year. Our most recent demo is here: https://vmware.slack.com/archives/C02LVJ1MTT8/p1681911826668369. We haven't fully built this, but with RadiumX, you'll be able to use remote GPUs from your local development environment, with hopefully minimal performance overhead even across slow networks, simply by replacing docker run with radium run. (If you wonder how we do this, I talked about it a little here: https://vmware.slack.com/archives/C01BSLUJDU0/p1666771957891539?thread_ts=1666770174.413489&cid=C01BSLUJDU0.) If this is interesting to you, please DM or e-mail me. We believe we've got compelling tech, that can make your ML work significantly easier, but it's not fully there yet. We'd like your help to find our biggest gaps and prioritize our work. Thanks!
This is from the Radium section at yesterday's MIPS demo meeting. In this, we demonstrate using Radium to compose one container that has access to an NVIDIA GPU with another that has access to an ML dataset, over increasing latencies between the nodes (up to a full second of latency!), while preserving close to bare-metal (!) performance of the ML application. Longer than a traditional "lightning" talk, but you can stop watching after 7 minutes if you don't care about the Q&A. :-)

Join us tomorrow (5/16) @ 9am PDT) for a Cloud AF Architecture Review - Malicious HTTP requests detection in k8s-based workloads using distributed tracing and Machine Learning by Enrique Corro Fuentes and Clemens Kolbitsch.
  • Microservices running on Kubernetes are trending as the most popular software application design architecture. Because of that, microservices have become the target of an increasing number of cyber-attacks; thus, newer security measures are in high demand. Machine learning-based anomaly detection has the potential to become a robust security measure to protect microservices systems. In this session, we discuss the Project Trinidad subsystems that implement ML models for detecting anomalous HTTP traffic among components of large and complex microservices architectures based on Kubernetes.
  • In this session we’ll be presenting the approaches we are using to build the anomaly detection ML models which includes a description about the feature extraction, model training and model testing processes. We’ll also talk about the computing characteristics of the existing models, including CPU, RAM, storage requirements to serve inference requests at a given speed rate.
